summary:
Some Moomin Analysis!!!
I finally watched episode 7 of Moominvalley and it was so good! I want to focus on the scene where...
body:
Some Moomin Analysis!!!

I finally watched episode 7 of Moominvalley and it was so good! I want to focus on the scene where Moomin helps Snufkin out of jail. As the two Hemulens argue about what to do with Snufkin, Moomin comes up with the plan to use the Woodies to help Snufkin make 5000 signs.

Moomin tells the Hemulens that Snufkin will make 5000 signs as punishment.

When Snufkin hears this, he thinks that Moomin is mad at Snufkin for leaving him alone at the party mentioned towards the beginning of the episode. He thinks that Moomin wants to punish Snufkin, and Snufkin is willing to accept that.

However, as was shown earlier, Moomin wasn’t planning that at all. Instead, he has the woodies help Snufkin make the signs.

Once Snufkin realizes Moomin’s plan, the two share a fond smile.

And, as the two characters leave the police station, they continue to smile warmly at each other.

Similarly to episode 2, the episode places an emphasis on Snufkin’s struggle of wanting his freedom while also wanting his relationship with Moomin. While Snufkin feels guilty for making Moomin sad, he also is sort of worried about becoming too attached and “loosing” his freedom.

When Snufkin talks to Little My about why he left Moominvalley, he says that sometimes he just needs his own space. However, Little My makes fun of Snufkin for saying that after seeing him interacting with the Woodies. In my opinion, Little My’s comment is meant to point out that while Snufkin may have felt overwhelmed at the party, he also probably left to “prove” that he could. It’s possible that he partially left just to show that his feelings for Moomin won’t keep him from leaving whenever he pleases.

However, Snufkin obviously can’t stop thinking about him leaving Moomin behind. Even though Moomin and Snorkmaiden were just locked up for Snufkin’s actions, the only reason that comes to Snufkin’s mind about why Moomin would want to punish him is Snufkin leaving. This shows that he still feels guilty for doing that and is maybe even worried that he damaged their relationship. So, the conflict of Snufkin possibility having to choose between freedom and Moomin comes to a head.

But, Moomin is not mad at Snufkin. Instead, he helps Snufkin escape from being in jail. Moomin helps Snufkin get his freedom back. Because Moomin never forces Snufkin to stay and always welcomed him back with open arms, the conflict between freedom and Moomin was never actually there for Snufkin to begin with. Rather than restrict, Snufkin’s relationship with Moomin gives Snufkin freedom to wander wherever he wants while always having a home to return to.
